04480nam a22006135i 9780292773134DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211992txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927731347 a10.7560/7653682doi  a(DE-B1597)588100  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPOL0400102bisacsh04a973.9230921 aHammond, Paul Y., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLBJ and the Presidential Management of Foreign Relations /cPaul Y. Hammond. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1992  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface. Where We Are Going: Presidential Management and the External Presidency -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Johnson's Foreign Relations: Toward a Broader Inquiry -- t2. The Larger Vision of Foreign Policy Management -- t3.1 The Indian Famine and Presidential Leverage -- t4. Johnson and Europe: The MLF and Alliance Politics -- t5. Influence, Strategy, and Western Europe -- t6. Vietnam: Normality and Innovation -- t7. Johnson's Foreign Policy Leadership in Larger Perspective -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this insightful study, Paul Y. Hammond, an experienced analyst of bureaucratic politics, adapts and extends that approach to explain and evaluate the Johnson administration’s performance in foreign relations in terms that have implications for the post–Cold War era. The book is structured around three case studies of Johnson’s foreign policy decision making. The first study examines economic and political development. It explores the way Johnson handled the provision of economic and food assistance to India during a crisis in India’s food policies. This analysis provides lessons not only for dealing with African famine in later years but also for assisting Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. The second case study focuses on U.S. relations with Western Europe at a time that seemed to require a major change in the NATO alliance. Here, Hammond illuminates the process of policy innovation, particularly the costs of changing well-established policies that embody an elaborate network of established interests. The third case study treats the Vietnam War, with special emphasis on how Johnson decided what to do about Vietnam. Hammond critiques the rich scholarship available on Johnson’s advisory process, based on his own reading of the original sources. These case studies are set in a larger context of applied theory that deals more generally with presidential management of foreign relations, examining a president’s potential for influence on the one hand and the constraints on his or her capacity to control and persuade on the other. It will be important reading for all scholars and policymakers interested in the limits and possibilities of presidential power in the post–Cold War era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJohnson, Lyndon B.-(Lyndon Baines),-1908-1973. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh1 aAnders, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedford, Emmette S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292773134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292773134/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK